  "reportSummary": "SENTINEL detected an emerging harmful algal bloom in western Lake Erie 6 days before official public health advisory. The system identified early microbial community shifts (cyanobacterial dominance rising from 12% to 35%) on July 14, corroborated by progressive sensor degradation (DO decline, pH rise, turbidity increase). Satellite confirmation followed on July 15. Source attribution (72% confidence) pointed to agricultural nutrient runoff exacerbated by warm temperatures and low circulation. The Digital Biosentinel predicted significant ecological impact, particularly to zooplankton (78% Daphnia mortality risk). Peak bloom extent reached ~620 km2 by July 20. The 6-day lead time could have enabled earlier drinking water intake adjustments and public notification.",
